In China, hardwood prices increased W/W, while softwood prices remained virtually flat. In Europe, hardwood and softwood prices remained flat W/W. The China NBSK-BHKP spread stood at \(\) 176\(/t, above the\) \ \(117 / t\) LT average.

Pricing trends: According to Fastmarkets, China net BHKP prices increased \(\) 19/t\(to\) \ \(512 / t\) , while NBSK prices remained stable at \(\) 689/t\(. BEKP import - equivalent resale price increased\) \ \(5/t\) W/W, standing at \(\) 494/t\(,\) \ \(19/t\) below the benchmark price. In Europe, BHKP and NBSK prices remained flat W/W at \(\) 1,000/t\(and\) \ \(1,496/t\) respectively. In USD, kraftliner prices in Europe remained stable W/W at \(\) 945/t\$

Market Highlights. Suzano and Eldorado have separately announced another price increase of \(\) 20/t\(for bleached eucalyptus kraft (BEK) pulp, effective for September sales. On the Shanghai Futures Exchange, the November 2025 NBSK contract continued carrying the largest monthly trading volume. It closed at\) \ \(601/t\) , after deducting logistics costs and value - added tax (VAT), on August 28th, down by\) \ \(16/t\) W/W, and standing \(\) 88/t\(below the benchmark price. (source: Fastmarkets).

ELDORADO PROPOSES PRICE INCREASES FOR SEPTEMBER BEK PULP SALES. Brazilian BEK pulp producer Eldorado has informed clients of further price increases effective with sales in September, sources told Fastmarkets on Tuesday August \(26^{\mathrm{th}}\) . Eldorado runs a single pulp line in Mato Grosso do Sul state in midwest Brazil and is targeting a second \(\) 20/\mathrm{t}\$ price increase for customers in China and Asia. Like other South American producers, Eldorado previously increased prices by \(\) 20/\mathrm{t}\$ for the same regions in the second half of August. Eldorado also announced an \(\) 80/\mathrm{t}\$ price hike for BEK sales in Europe and North America, effective from September \(1^{\mathrm{st}}\) - a similar increase to the one proposed by Suzano on August \(21^{\mathrm{st}}\) . (Fastmarkets)

\* PPPC PUBLISHED JULY WORLD PULP PRODUCERS REPORT. Worldwide pulp shipments totaled 4.576mt in July, decreasing \(6.7\%\) M/M from 4.905mt. In contrast, July shipments gained \(7.3\%\) Y/Y from 4.265mt. Producers often move large volumes at the end of each quarter for financial reasons, so a shipment decline amid a summer slowdown is typical, with June marking the second quarter's end. Inventories at global bleached softwood kraft (BSK) market pulp producers closed July at 50 days of supply, flat from June results, according to the PPPC. Bleached hardwood kraft (BHK) producer stocks increased to 45 days of supply, a 1-day increase. World- 20 chemical market pulp statistics represent \(82\%\) of global capacity and includes data from 17 currently producing counties. (Fastmarkets) See details at: LatAm Pulp & Paper: Pulp Monthly Update — July 2025 (27 Aug 2025)

\* BRAZILIAN PULP EXPORTS UPDATE, \(4^{\mathrm{th}}\) WEEK OF AUGUST. According to MDIC data, accumulated Brazilian pulp exports in the \(4^{\mathrm{th}}\) week of August amounted to 1,313kt. The daily exports for the month amounted to 82.1kt/d, \(1\%\) below the 83kt/d from July but \(46\%\) above the 56.1kt/d from the same month of last year. The accumulated average export price until this week reached \(\) 424/t\(, stable compared to July's\) \ \(426/t\) average, but \(32\%\) below from August of 2024 \(\) 620/t\(average. (MDIC)

\* FIRE AT NAVIGATOR'S SETUBAL P&P MILL REDUCES MARKET PULP AVAILABILITY BY 25KT. Following a fire at its Setúbal pulp and paper (P&P) mill in Portugal in July, The Navigator Company (Navigator) said on Thursday \(28^{\mathrm{th}}\) August that the incident had reduced the market pulp volumes from its Aveiro and Figueira da Foz facilities by around 25kt during the summer period. According to the company, the fire affected the Setúbal mill's bleaching area, caused no injuries, and was quickly resolved. Pulp production at the site was temporarily idled and resumed on August \(11^{\mathrm{th}}\) . (Fastmarkets)

\* PAPERBOARD INDUSTRY ADJUSTS PRODUCTION UNDER PRESSURE FROM IMPORTS AND TARIFF HIKES. Paperboard companies in Brazil are reducing production and halting expansion projects in response to oversupply in the domestic market and uncertainties in foreign trade. From January to May, Papirus, one of the four largest paperboard producers in the country, halted production equivalent to 36 days, leading to the suspension of the purchase of a new machine that would increase production by 150kt. According to data from the Secretariat of Foreign Trade (Secex), imports of three types of paperboard totaled 98kt in 1H25. Between 2020 and May 2025, the share of
imported product in the Brazilian market reached 780kt, equivalent to one year of domestic industry sales. (Valor)

\* SUN PAPER TO BUILD 700KTPY RECYCLED BOARD MACHINE AT YANDIAN MILL IN SHANDONG, CHINA. Shandong Sun Paper announced on August 28th that it is planning to build a new 700ktpy recycled linerboard machine at its Yandian mill, in Jining city, Shandong province, which currently runs a 450ktpy UFP machine and four specialty paper machines with a combined capacity of 133ktpy. The producer said the total investment into the project will be no more than 1.53bn yuan (\$214.5m), and the construction will take 18 months. The company said its mills in Shandong have huge virgin-fiber based paper and board (P&B) capacity, and the new line will be able reduce its reliance on market pulp and improve cost effectiveness. (Fastmarkets)

Our YE25 PT is derived using the avg. of a multiple and a DCF valuation. In the first approach, we use an EV/EBITDA multiple of \(5.9x\) — in line with the stock's five- year average — on our 2026e EBITDA. In our DCF approach, we use a \(8.1\%\) WACC with a \(1.0\%\) LT growth rate.
- Higher pulp prices- Stronger demand for paper products- Market share gains on Softys- BioCMPC ramps-up faster than initially expected
- Lower than anticipated pulp prices- Weaker demand for paper products- Market share losses on Softys- Execution risk on the BioCMPC ramp-up

Our YE25 PT is derived using the avg. of a Sum- of- the- Parts and a DCF valuation. In the first approach, we use average comparable EV/EBITDA multiple for each subsidiary on our 2026e EBITDA. In our DCF approach, we use a WACC of \(8\%\) (vs \(8.1\%\) previous) with a \(0\%\) LT growth rate.
- Higher pulp prices- Better margins on the fuel distribution business
- Lower pulp prices- Softwood price premium drops- Significantly lower volumes on the fuel distribution business due to increased EV penetration

Our YE25 PT is derived using the avg. of a multiple and a DCF valuation. In the first approach, we use a P/E multiple of \(15.7x\) — in line with the stock's five- year average — on our 2026e EPS. In our DCF approach, we use a \(8.7\%\) WACC with a \(2.0\%\) LT growth rate.
- MXN strengthens beyond our base case- Commodity prices decrease faster and to lower than anticipated levels- Volumes grow above our expectations- KCM gains market share
MXN weakens beyond our base case Commodity prices stay higher for longer Volumes grow below our expectations KCM loses market share

Our YE25 PT is derived using the average of a multiple \((50\%)\) and a DCF \((50\%)\) valuation. In the first approach, we use an EV/EBITDA multiple of \(7.3x\) (vs. \(7.4x\) before) - in line with the stock's five- year historical average - on our 2026e EBITDA. In the DCF approach, we use a \(9.4\%\) WACC with a \(1\%\) LT growth rate.
Above expected GDP driving higher demand for Klabin's products Stronger pulp or paper packaging prices
Lower pulp or paper packaging prices Lower- than- expected demand for Klabin's products Execution risk on growth projects Machines certification takes longer than expected

Our price target is derived using the average of a multiple \((50\%)\) and a DCF \((50\%)\) valuation. In the first approach, we use an EV/EBITDA multiple of \(5.7x\) - 0.5 std dev below the stock's 5y average - on our 2026e EBITDA. In the DCF approach, we use a \(8.0\%\) WACC with a \(1\%\) LT growth rate. We set our target multiple 0.5 standard deviation below historical level as we remain conservative in our approach and continue to account for a M&A overhang.
Higher than expected pulp prices, driven by stronger demand and/or supply- side issues Weaker BRL Accretive M&A transaction Faster than anticipated ramp- up of Cerrado
Lower than expected pulp prices Further strengthening of BRL Dilutive M&A transaction that materially increases leverage Execution risk related to the ramp- up of Cerrado
